## Overview

This analysis examines which emerging dental technologies are being
tested in registered clinical trials and how research activity has
changed over time. Data was retrieved from ClinicalTrials.gov — the U.S.
federal registry of clinical studies worldwide.

Total trials analyzed: 4,422 dental trials (2000-2024)

Technologies examined: Dental Implants, Lasers, AI-assisted diagnosis,
CAD/CAM digital workflows, Teledentistry, and Robotics

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Methods

All dental-related trials were downloaded from ClinicalTrials.gov and
imported into R. Trials were classified into technology categories using
keyword detection across trial titles and summaries. Analysis was
conducted using R with tidyverse packages.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Key Findings

### 1. Trial Counts by Technology Category

![](output/category_totals.png)

Dental implant research dominates the field with 1,285 registered trials
— more than all other technology categories combined. CAD/CAM digital
workflows rank second with 193 trials, reflecting the rapid adoption of
digital dentistry in clinical practice over the past decade.

### 2. Technology Trends Over Time

![](output/trend_chart.png)

Implant trial registration shows consistent growth from 2000 onwards,
reflecting sustained commercial and regulatory interest. Laser therapy
maintains steady research activity. Emerging technologies including AI,
CAD/CAM, and teledentistry remain small in absolute numbers but show
recent growth.

### 3. The AI Story

![](output/ai_trend.png)

AI-related dental trials show near-zero registration before 2018,
followed by rapid growth concentrated in 2021-2024. This pattern
reflects the broader adoption of machine learning in medical imaging,
with dental radiograph interpretation emerging as the primary clinical
application.

### 4. Who Funds Dental Research?

![](output/funder_chart.png)

Unlike pharmaceutical research where industry funding dominates, dental
technology research is primarily academically funded. This has
implications for evidence quality and publication bias — academic trials
are generally considered more independent but may have fewer resources
for large-scale multi-site studies.

